SIMPLE: suspend
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Suspend
<hw>Sus*pend"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Suspended</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Suspending</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F. <ets>suspendre</ets>, or
OF. <ets>souspendre</ets> (where the prefix is L. <ets>subtus</ets>
below, from <ets>sub</ets> under), L. <ets>suspendere</ets>,
<ets>suspensum</ets>; pref. <ets>sus-</ets> (see <er>Sub-</er>) +
<ets>pendere</ets> to hang. See <er>Pedant</er>, and cf.
<er>Suspense</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To attach to
something above; to hang; <as>as, to <ex>suspend</ex> a ball by a
thread; to <ex>suspend</ex> a needle by a loadstone</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To make to depend; <as>as, God hath
<ex>suspended</ex> the promise of eternal life on the condition of
obedience and holiness of life</as>.</def> <mark>[Archaic]</mark>
<rj><au>Tillotson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To cause to cease for a time; to hinder from
proceeding; to interrupt; to delay; to stay.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Suspend</qex> your indignation against my brother.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The guard nor fights nor fies; their fate so near⟦br⟧
At once <qex>suspends</qex> their courage and their fear.</q>
<rj><qau>Denham.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To hold in an undetermined or undecided state;
<as>as, to <ex>suspend</ex> one's judgment or opinion</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Locke.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To debar, or cause to withdraw temporarily, from any
privilege, from the execution of an office, from the enjoyment of
income, etc.; <as>as, to <ex>suspend</ex> a student from college; to
<ex>suspend</ex> a member of a club.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Good men should not be <qex>suspended</qex> from the exercise of
their ministry and deprived of their livelihood for ceremonies which are
on all hands acknowledged indifferent.</q> <rj><qau>Bp.
Sanderson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To cause to cease for a time from operation or
effect; <as>as, to <ex>suspend</ex> the habeas corpus act; to
<ex>suspend</ex> the rules of a legislative body.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>To support in a liquid, as an
insoluble powder, by stirring, to facilitate chemical action.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To suspend payment</b></col> <fld>(Com.)</fld>, <cd>to
cease paying debts or obligations; to fail; -- said of a merchant, a
bank, etc.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To hang; interrupt; delay; intermit; stay;
hinder; debar.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1454 --></p>

<p><ent>Suspend</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Suspend
<hw>Sus*pend"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To cease from
operation or activity; esp., to stop payment, or be unable to meet
obligations or engagements (said of a commercial firm or a
bank).</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Suspender</ent>⟦br⟧
